Xylocarpus mekongensis

    Authority   Pie.
      Family    Magnoliopsida:Rosidae:Sapindales:Meliaceae
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 10955

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION
   Medium-sized, evergreen or briefly deciduous, glabrous tree reaching of
   10-20 m in height, with a trunk diameter up to 1 m in diameter with
   very short or even no buttresses and an elaborated above ground root
   system. USES The bark of the bole is rich in tannin. It is used for
   tanning heavy hides, thoughening fishing-nets and dying cloth. The wood
   is of good quality, but the trunk is often crooked and hollow. The wood
   is used for boat building, nails, house-posts, small objects, furniture
   and firewood. Bark and seeds have medicinal properties. GROWING PERIOD
   Perennial. COMMON NAMES Pussur, Ail. FURTHER INF Scientific synonyms:
   X. gangeticus, X. australasicus, Carapa moluccensis. Pussur can be
   found on tidal mud of mangrove swamps, especially towards their upper
   limits. Photosynthesis pathway C3.

   Sources
   SOURCES (X. mekongensis Pierre)
   Tomlinson P 1986 pp 281-282 [SAL]
   Troup R 1921 pp 186-187 [DRA, TEXT, TEMP, RAIN]
   Aronson J 1989 pp 64 [SAL]
   National RC 180 pp 52-54 [DRA, SAL, TEXT, TEMP, KTMP, RAIN, DEP]
   Lemmens R 1991 pp 128-130 [USE, DRA, TEXT, SAL]

